data.content:
## Migration Analysis

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement — aborting a thread that exceeds a time limit.

**Key issue:** `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. The fundamental shift is from *preemptive* cancellation (runtime injects an exception) to *cooperative* cancellation (code voluntarily checks a token).

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always dispose it
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Task-based model integrates with cancellation |
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Cooperative cancellation via token; abort is gone |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No equivalent needed — cancellation doesn't auto-rethrow |
| `Func<T> work` | `Func<CancellationToken, T> work` | Work **must** receive the token to cooperate |

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ComputeExpensiveResult(data),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => ComputeExpensiveResult(data, ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

The work method must check the token:

```csharp
T ComputeExpensiveResult(Data data, CancellationToken token)
{
    foreach (var item in data.Items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return BuildResult();
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, the token only takes effect at checkpoints. If `work` never checks the token, it runs forever. Place `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` in loops and between expensive operations. |
| **Token must flow through the full call chain** | Every async/long-running method must accept and forward the `CancellationToken`. One method ignoring it stalls cancellation at that point. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` ignores the token** | Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or `Task.Delay(ms, token)`. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and callbacks. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Let it propagate. Only catch at the top-level orchestration point (here we convert it to `TimeoutException`). |
| **Uncooperative code (can't modify to accept token)** | If the `Func<T>` runs code you can't change (e.g., third-party library), move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET. |
